        Official Singles Chart on 29/10/2021

        29 October 2021 - 4 November 2021

        The Official Singles Chart Top 100 reflects the UK’s biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1. View the biggest songs of 2025.

        WEEKLY CHART REVIEW (28/10/2021 – 04/11/2021)

        🔴 (Negative)

        1) The Top 10 this week has the exact same songs in it as it did last week! The quality of the songs in it aren’t precisely bad, but it’s also kind of boring to see.

        2) ‘My Heart Goes [La Di Da]’ misses the Top 10 once again! This might’ve been its final chance with the inevitable takeover from all the ‘=’ tracks coming next week.

        3) ‘Life Goes On’ is still sticking around! I don’t get what people can find appealing about this song. The vocals might be among the most grating I’ve heard in a hit song all year!

        4) 'Let Somebody Go' suffered a big second week drop! One of the best tracks on Coldplay's new album in my opinion.

        5) ‘Visiting Hours’ gets placed on ACR as expected! Even despite the album boost next week, it’ll probably still drop out of the chart entirely because it won’t be one of the three best performing tracks from ‘=’! Such a shame because I don’t think it’s likely that anything on the album will beat it in terms of quality.

        🟠 (Mixed)

        1) ‘Red Light Green Light’ makes a fairly high debut & let’s be honest, while Digga D is certainly a name we’ve been seeing in the charts for a while now, the only reason that this is here is because of how popular Squid Game has become (which I don’t plan on watching, just not for me personally!). Anyway, after the train wreck that was ‘Wasted’ from a weeks back, this is certainly a step in the right direction. You can definitely tell that the song is aiming for the dark, eery vibe of the aforementioned series with the heavy drill beat, the tight flow, the aggressive & direct lyrics, all of which Digga D can sell fairly well! If anything, the song can feel a bit choppy in places & some of the ab-libs sound really out of places, but even the autotune isn’t a massive problem here either. So yeah, probably nothing I’ll personally be revisiting, but I get the appeal behind this! I’ll take it.

        2) ‘Just A Notion’ missed out on the Top 40! Given the huge drop it took from the First Look to Monday’s update, we all knew this was coming. Even then, for as much as I love ABBA as a group, this is far from their best song & probably my least favourite of the three singles they’ve released since making their recent comeback.

        3) 'Better Days' (NEIKED) makes an appearance here, but I'll start to get excited for it if or when it goes Top 40!

        🟢 (Positive)

        1) ‘Easy On Me’ gets a second week at #1! Again, it’s in this section of the review, because, you know, Adele.

        2) ‘Meet Me At Our Spot’ is still moving up! I’m hoping that this can eventually go Top 10, although my expectations for it might be a little high given that it still has a while to go & next month is going to be absolutely manic for albums, but all the big radio stations love it now, so that at least gives me some hope.

        3) ‘Tell Me Something Good’ continues to climb with it! It can be a very tough sell getting an EDM remake of a 70’s classic to work, especially to older chart fans who grew up with the original classics, but this remix seems to do just that thankfully.

        4) ‘Moth To A Flame’ just about debuts in the Top 40 & this for me is Swedish House Mafia’s real comeback single, after the disappointments that were ‘It Gets Better’ & ‘Lifetime’ from earlier this year! Granted, I doubt this would’ve done anywhere near as well or even charted at all without The Weeknd teaming up with them, but you know what, he proves yet again that he sounds in his element on 80’s style production & his vocals continue to have that irresistible smoothness to it, whilst also sounding notably severe & that’s a hard combination to get right in the mainstream nowadays! The drop is actually more relaxing than anything too exciting & you think that might be boring on paper, but it isn’t. My only criticism is that the outro could’ve been a little less dragged out, but when the beat has such a uplifting swell & groove behind, that doesn’t put me off this one bit! Hopefully it can climb a bit more in the coming weeks. Britain, keep buying & streaming it, we need more smashes like this here!

        5) ‘24/5’ matches its peak thanks to Mimi Webb’s new EP! Honestly, ‘Seven Shades Of Heartbreak’ is the best EP I’ve heard all year & this track is definitely a highlight from it.

        6) ‘Seventeen Going Under’ not only stayed in the Top 40 this week, but it actually went back up a bit! I expected the hype behind this song to fade with Sam Fender’s new album, but it fortunately looks like that didn’t happen.

        7) ‘Who You Are’ also managed to sneak in this week! I had fairly high expectations when arguably one of the most famous garage singers of the century was teaming up with the artist who previously provided the vocals to my favourite song of the decade so far & yeah, this absolutely lived up to them! Look, for Craig David & MNEK, melodies have always been their strong point & they harmonise beautifully in this. I also love how sweet the lyrics are too, where they still see a connection with somebody they admire for their personality, even despite it seems like the whole world is turning against them! The song already hits a very motivational note for me, but it also has that uplifting element to it, especially thanks to the vibrant garage backdrop courtesy of Digital Farm Animals (who isn’t officially credited on the song). Either way, Craig David & MNEK have come up with a formula here! I really hope that they can collaborate again in the future if anything they work on is going to reach the same heights that this does. Amazing song!

        8) ‘Bad Day’ to be dropping off now! It’s in my Top 10 worst songs of the year so far, so good riddance to it, haha.

        9) Elton John debuted at #1 on the albums chart, just two weeks after he got the #1 single here!

        My latest personal chart (replace the * with an “o”): www.crownnote.c*m/charts/piran/pirans-top-50-12
